{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_cookie_ver02/data/sn89053308/00517177258/1923092701/0798.xml":{"full_text":"The Fitzgerald Leader\nENTERPRISE and PRESS\nOfficial Organ City of Fitzgerald\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY\nBy The Leader Publishing Company\nSubscription Price, per Annum:-._______ $1.50\nEntered at the Post (\u00bbm\u00e9c\u2014\u00bbzt Fitzgerald as Second Class\nMail Matter under Act of Congress, March 18, 1897.\nSIDHOR GEILDERS 1. Hditof.\nMrs. MAUD GELDERS, ....-.-.._News Editor\ni R\nKates lor display advertising furnished on application.\nLocal Readers 10c per line for each insertion. No ad\ntaken for less than 30 cents. AMERICAN PRESS\nASSOCIATION, Foreign Advertising Representatives.\nGOOD TIMES AHEAD-- Discussing with the\ntwo banks of the gity the present year end situa\ntion and the outlook for another year indicates that\nthough times have been tight, people are not broke\nby any means, but have this year learned a mighty\ngood Tesson\u2014the lesson of appreciating a dollar\nand the lesson of economy and saving. These bank\ners are all the while peering into the future to\nguide away from dangers and they believe that\nwith normal weather next year we are going to\nmake good yields of several money crops, includ\ning nice yield of cotton, peanuts, tobacco, hogs,\nchickens and eggs, cream, oats, potatoes, syrup,\ncte,, just such a combination as will give the\nfarmer 2 chance at several money bringers so that\nif one source fails he will have other saurces for\ngain.\nIn other sections of Georgia this year where\ntiney had reasonable weather and poisoned cotton\nthey got real good crops of cotton and in many\nsections lots of other stuff to bring money.\nWhere tobacco was farmed under the direction\nof experts the countics are flourishing. Several\ncommunities have marketed car load lots of pep\npers, cucumbers, tomatoes, hogs, poultry and farm\np roducts can be grown here giving work for the\nfarmer to do all the year round and cash coming\ni 1 every week in the year these bankers feel that\n21l we have got to do is to think wisely in planning\ncrops, work them intelligently, be patient, stay\nclose on the job and grow altogether enough for\ncar load shipments and by another fall find our\nselves in good shape and really thankful for the\nvaluable lessons of 1023\nThe surprising thing about this years situation is\nthat farmers have passed through the year without\nLorrowing any money at all, nearly for the years\noperations. One explanation is that they have\n1:0bly done their best this year cutting down every\nunneeded expense and have had money coming in\nseveral of them for something, chickens, hogs,\nmilk, cattle or truck, almost every week in 1923.\nThese bankers seem to helieve that in a vear or\ntwo we shall have better times than we have ever\nFad\u2014that is we will be operating on a basis of\nM;\\N\\' CROPS instead of just cotton and not\nsending our money away for anything to make\nthese cre ps with exeept a little fertilizer and some\nfarming implements so that the money coming\nto the farmer will STICK with him. V\nLet's take courage from this bright prospect.\ne e Dmeemsmn e DTIE Nt prospect.\nMr. and Mrs. E Faulkner announce\nthe birth of a baby boy on Sept. 21.\nMr and Mrs. 1 W. Shultz motored\nto Douglas Sunday where they were\nthe guests of Mrs Henry Sapp.\nMr. Lee McGlamory of Hawkins\nville spent Sunday with h's sister Mrs,\nH. M. Bonds.\nMr, H C Weaver .of Fllavilleig\nthe guest of Mr and Mrs. J. E. Weav\ner th's weck.\nMrs_ Bond of Jacksonville is spend\ning a few weeks with Yer granddauoh\nter Mrs. W W Sims on north Main.\nMr. and Mrs C R Rosea are now\nat home at 215 W. Palm\nMiss Mamie Smith spent a few days\nin Atlanta last week.\nMrs. C. H. Gill and father Mr, H.\nC. Chanle returned Saturdav from A\npleasant six weeks visit to relatives in\nKansas and Oklahoma\nRETURN POCKETBOOK AND\nKEEP CONTENTS\u2014Lost one black\npockethood, fold, containing one dol\nlar bl and some <malt change and\nB. L. F, receipts. Finder can keep the\nmone\u00a5 for the return of the pocket\nbook and rece'pts to Leader-Enter-\nprise. ti\n\nMrs. Geo. Mcleod and dangh(cr'\nMiss Irene and Mrs. Paxon of Abbe\nville were visitors to the city today,\nMrs. Jack Harroll is visiting her\nmother Mrs Crawiord this week.\nMrs, P. T. Craig has returned from\n2 visit to home folks in South Caro\nlina.\nMr. and Mrs. Geo Lane are at\nnome acvain after a pleagant week in\nRirmingham, Ala.\nThe Baptist Migsionary society will\nmeet at the Baptist church Monday\nafternoon for the annual election of\nofficers,\nAlderman Lacey Ennis and Roy\nFuller returned th's afternoon from\nan evtensive visit to North and South\nCarolina,\nMr. and Mrs Henry Powell and\nMrs Midena Rogers and little daugh\nter Harriet spent Sunday :in Albany\nmeeting the'r consin from New Or\nleans who is visiting there.\nMr. M. Gottlieh returned th's morn\ning from a business trip \u2018o Manches\nter,\nCol. Sam Kassewitz of Macon was\na visitor with home folks on Friday\nand Saterday.\nMr C. 1. Tavlor of Ta'keonville. Fla\nis a guest of Dr. and Mrs Frank\nWard,\nMrs, L. McCarty and daughter\nFl'zabeth and Mr, and Mrs, C B\nWatts and children composed an au\ntomohile sarty to Americus today to\nvisit relatives,\ni iects\nMiss Ir's Peterson of Douglas is\nthe ponular guest of her sister Mrs.\nBruce Martin and Mig Laura Whit\niey,\nThe Kiwanis Club and the Chamber\nof Commerce have posted a huletin\nboard in the Blue and Gray Park, ad\nvertising the churches\nrMrSs Harry Arthur had as her guest\nlagt week, Prof, and Mrs. J. E. Math\n1s of Americus,\nMr. Harold Parrott of Atlanta was\nvisiting h's parents, Mr. and Mrs, 3\nA, Porrot on Sunday.\nS\nMrs, Myra Dewey and daughter,\nHope, have arrived from Wisconsin\ni te make their home with Mrs Deweys\nmother Mrs. A C Justice,\nj Mr andl Mrs T D. Padgett spent\nthe week end with their son E A, Pad\njgett on west Altamaha,\nG\nf Misg Lizzie Norman of Norman\nPark spent two days in the city last\nweek visiting her sister Mrs. Chester\nStrickland.\nFURNITURE\nAT\ne\nAuction\nAt 10 O\u2019clock\nSaturday September 29th, all\nof the Household Goods of\nMrs. G. S. Willcox will be Sold\nat Auction to the highest Bid\nder. Sale will be at Residence\n-405 South Grant Street\nW. W. Martin, Auctioneer\nFNI\nI WILL DRAIN MY FISH POND OCTOBER IIBTH AND\nINVITE THE FISHERMEN OF THIS COUNTY LA PAR.\nTICIPATE IN THE BIGGEST FISH CATCH OF THE\nSEASON,\nSeigning and Gigging Not Allowed. Th: Fish Pond is between\nFitzgerald and Mystic and is full of fish. Come out and get your\nshare. Tickets for all day Fishing\u2014s 2 00,\nA. B. C. DORMINEY\n\nNO \u201cFOR RENT\u201d SIGNS-\u2014Fitzgerald has little\nneed for signs showing property for rent, for near\nly every home is rented before it is vacated. While\nsome who contemplate moving to a new town may\nbe inluenced to locate in a place where the \u201cfor\nrent\u201d signs are plentiful, the chances are they\nwould never buy property for fear it might have\nto stand vacant. i\nB S\nA CHANGE NEEDED-Ii reckless specders on\nly caused their own deaths, there would be little\ncause for grief on the part of the public, but ir\nmost cases they escape while their innocint vic\ntims are sent to their graves or crippled for life.\nS e G e e s\nBUSINESS STABILITY-\u2014All the great banks\nand mercantile surveyors agree that the business\nof the summer has given evidence of stability.\nSummer is not a time of business. The farmer\u2019s\ncrops are yet to be harvested\u2014and, what is eco\nnomically more important\u2014marketed. Entire in\ndustries are forced to mark time, and for instance,\nmanufacturers of cotton goods. The hazards of\nthe crop, with a negligible carry-over have all\nsummer tantalized the first purchasers of the great\nsouthern staple, with the result that the mills\nhave been inactive. Increasing business at the\niagend of the summer, however, indicates not on-\nIy the growth of confidence among manufacturers\nbut argues the existence of a reservoir of demand\nwhich will soon be returned loose. The same\ntendencies are seen in other dull lines. A few oth\ners, notably the shoe trade, are already enjoying\n1 period of relative boom.\nEDITOR\u2019S FIRST DUTY\u2014The two purposes of\ncountry newspaper are to make money and to\nserve the community. Making money is put first\nfor the paper that is not making money cannot\nserve the community, it is bound to be a poor down\nat the heels affair. You owe it to your community\n\u2018o make your paper make money.\n\nRECKLESS DRIVING\u2014 Cannot users of Ben\nil County roads take a warning from the several\naccidents that have occurred lately? Fortunately\nno fatality or even serious injury has resulted in\nthe past two weeks, but it is only good fortune or\nthe will of God that prevent it.\nAt least two cars have been wrecked by drivers\npresumably under the influence of liquor. Some\nthing should he done to stop this, some lesson\ngiven before the community 1s shocked by some\nheavy tragedy.\nThe man who dilutes his easoline with alcohol\nwill find trouble just as surely as if he advertised\ntor it in the Leader. After the latter way would\nnot entail the risk to other often innocent parties\nto the affair,\nT s\nWHAT IT REALLY MEANS-\u2014Did you ever\nstop to think that when you trade in another town\nvou injure vour home town in the same degree\nthat you help the town you trade in? When you\nFelpi the other town vou naturally hurt your town.\nTherefore play the game safe. Trade at home.\ne P e\nMr. Coolidge has been president all this time\nand hasn\u2019t introduced a single pet word or slogan\nVEL.\nMr and Mrs Dan McKay announce\nthe birth of a fine baby girl at their\nhome Monday.\nMr and Mrs. H Wideman were\nvisitors in Waycross several days last\nweek.,\nMrs, Floy Clarke of Dublin, the\nguest of Mrs. H. A. Mauthis the past\ntwo weeks is now visiting relatives in\nOcilla. Mrs. Mathis is spending the\nday there also,\nMrs. T. P. Pounds of Sandusky, O,\nis the guest of Mrs J T Reddick on\nWest Pine St,\nMrs, Russell Smith of Valdosta is\nvisiting her s\u2019ster Mrs. Turner Brown\non west Pine\nTHE LEADER-ENTERPRISE AND PRESS, THURSDAY, SEPTEMBER 27, 1923\nEDDE;IT[\u2018TES SPO%\u2018%.IGI\u2014ITS\n's S s\nTHINGs [YB rEcPLE_~\nW~ By Mil's Maude Gelders\nROME\u2019'S POPULAR CURB\nMARKET\nThey say the curb market has al\nmost lost its identity as a market for\nfarm produce. A writer in the Con\nstitution says it has become a combi\nnation of side show, menagerie, sec\nond hand furniture store, soft drink\nemporium, stockyard and art musuem.\nAll of which goes to show the pop\nularity of the place. It is almost back\nto the old time barter system and at\nleast does away with the present day\ncommercial octopus the middle man.\n\nFAVORS CONSOLIDATION\nSYSTEM\nArecent interview on the subject\nof consolidating the railroads into\nlarge systems as provided in the trans\nportation act of 1920 shows that Pres\nident Conlidge favors the plan. The\nconsolidation being permitted as a\nvoluntary accomplishment by the ra\u2018l\nroads themselves, the 'amalgamation\nhas not vet been affected as there is\nno present practical scheme of agree\nment_\nBIRSE ELITERS STILL IN\nCOMMISSION\nModeern methods of communication\nhave not yet ousted the first reliable\n?\ufb02iers in Uncle Sam's military serv'ce\nand even now there are 1400 carrier\np'geons drawing rations at 22 differ\nent army posts along the Mexican bor\nder, in Hawaiia, in the Canal Zone,\nin the Phillipines, and at reserve head\nquarters iy New Jersey.\n\nA BOON TO SUEFEFERTPS\nA recent announcemen! he N\nY. Radium Institute thai the l:rgest\ndeposit of radium yet d'scovered s\nnow available from Ferghana a new\npoint of access is a message that means\ngreat advantage to science and rel'ef\nto many more people than was possible\nheretofore with such limited amounts\navailable at this time. The price too\nwas pmohibitive to many hospitals.\nColorado is remembered as furnish\ning the first supply with prices rang\ning $lOO,OOO and above for a gram.\nThen a Belg'an plant began extract\ning radium from African ore which\nsnon reduced the price to $75,000. In\nJu'y the total amount of the precious\nproduct in the whole world was 8\nounces, three being retained in the\nTS\nACHILLES HERD\nThe fleet mancuvers of last spring\nabout Panama Canal demonstrated\nthat the Canal was vulnerable from\nthe land! side in spite of jungles here\ntofore deemed sufficient protection.\nHence there are now one the way\nfrom the headquarters at Fort Meade,\na number \u00bbf the caterpillar tractors\nand one light and one heavy tank with\na detail of officers and men to con\nduct experiments in the region and\nshould the outcome he satisfactory the\nWar Department will at once throw\na defense of approximately 125 -of\u2018\nthese \u201cmechanical elephants\u201d into the\nzone,\nCETTING ACQUAINTED\nWITH GEORGIA\nA Savannah editor has said that\n\u201cnobody is acquainted w'th Georgia\nwho has not visited her great port, who\nhas not seen Tybee Ligh*, who has\nnot trod the ground that Oglethorpe\ntrod, seen the place where Sergeant\nTasper dfed in heroism, seen the places\nwhere Washington and Lafayette vis\n\u2018ted, where John Wesley preached,\nwhere (Ceo. Whitfield labored, where\n\u2018the bloodiest battle of the Revolution\nwas fouight, where Savannah made the\nlast courageous stand against Sherm\nan, where great ocean steamers come\nto load and unload, where enough su\ngar is made to sweeten all the tea and\ncoffee consumed in Georg'a, where\nthe matches you use are made, where\nhistory and modern industry and\nmodern pleasure are hand in hand for\nyour instruction and enjoyment\u201d; Yea\nverily and Monday, September 24th\nwas the happy day.\nNOTICE PRIMARY ELECTION\nBy the authority vested in the Exe\ncut've Committee of the City of Fitz\ngerald by the Charter of the City, a\nPrimary election is hereby called: by\nsaid committee to be held on October\nOth, 1923, for the nomination of candi\n\u2018dates for the following offices:\nMayor, City Treasurer, five Aldermen\nat Large, one member of the Water,\nLight and Bond Commiss\u2018on, Presi\ndent of the Board of Education, and\none member of the Board of Educa\ntion from cach of the four wards of\nthe City. The Registration books will\nclose on September 29th, at 6 p. m.\nCandidates for either of the offices\nto be nominated must file their names\nwith the unders\u2019gned \u201cSecretary for\nthe Executive Comm\u2019ttee and\npay the entrance fee =s per attached\nschedule on or before 6 p. m., Sept.\n20th,\nThe election is to be held under\nthe Australian Ballot Syctem. Polls to\nopen at 7 a. m. and close at 6 p.m.\nble yourselves therefore under the\nMayar oLI e o S 0\nCite: Brensurer Lo iio.. $lO.OO\nWater, Light and Bond Com.__slo.oo\nAlderngl 00l 8 U 0\nStheol Board _.olaieiciioo L 500\nIsidor Gelders, Chairman,\ndS2O Will S. Haile, Secretary.\nSAVING GEORGIA BABIES\nFor many years there was in Gaines\nville, Ga.,, a phys'cian of great state\nrepute as a baby specialist. He died\nsome time ago. Perhaps some Atlan\nta doctors have taken first rank since\nthen but from now on for five years\nAthens will be the scat of one of three\nspecial baby clinics to be oconducted\nfor that period of time in each section\nof the country financed by a common\nwealth fund of $90,000,000 in all, Athens\nis in fact a fourth one in this south\neastern section and won over 32 other\ncities including Danville and Char\nlottesville, Va, A vanguard of special\nists for baby ills will soon arrive to\nconduct the clinic and probably to\nsave the lives of thousands of Geor\ngia babies that will be carried to\nthem,\nx x\nPOOR CIVIC FABRIC\nA writer of note, speaking of grea*\nmen particularly American statesmen\nof the past says that even Franklin or\nJefferson could never have carried\ntheir projects through with such flim\nsy civic material as our day produces.\nHe says we are poor patriots these\ndays. The decisive battles of '76 do\nnot interest people as do Dempsey and\nBabe Ruth nor are they so enthused\nover a 1 new navy aviation speed of 259\nmiles an hour as over a Boston man\u2019s\n410 yard golf drive. How many can\nrecite the Star Spangled Banner or\nthe Iseclaration of Independence? he\nsays. Here then may be a reason for\nthe frequent query, \u201cWhy do we nev\ner have any great men or orators in\nthe present day to equal those of whom\nall history is proud in the past?\u201d\u2019 Av\nerage citizenship too is at low par.\n*x\nGOD SPEED THE NEGROES\nThis is the tenor of a speech recent-\nIy made before the editors of the Bth\nand Gh districts by Judge Fortson,\nspeaking of the negro migration, He\nsa\u2018d: \u201cThere is no section of the earth\nmore richly endowed with natural ad\nvantages and yet we have lagged be\nhind the rest of the nation in wealth,\nmanufactures, commerce, agriculture,\nand education, Can it be doubted! that\nthis backwardness is due to the pres\nence of 12,000,000 negroes pauperized\nand illiterate? As the negroes in in\ncreasing number migrate northward to\nthe industrial centers, white men of\nsuperior standards of living, of more\nintelhgence, more energy and greater\nindustry will take their places. Our\nfarms will improve, labor prices will\nadvance, manufacturing will increase\nand the South will catch step with the\nrest of the nation. To the negroes who\nleave, T say God speed. I rejoice in\nit. To the South it is as the first pale\nravs of the dawn or a better day.\u201d\nMr. and Mrs. Purvis and children\nhave moved hcre from Douglias and\n\u00b0re occupying the pretty bungalow on\nMerrimac Drive recently remodeled by\nDr Frank Ward,\n49\nEXCEPTIONALLY FINE STATEMENT IN TIMES LIKE THESE.\nAN E RXOBANGE BADTTONLALL BABR.\nCondition at time of Government Call Sept., 14th.\nCapital Stock $lOO 000 00\nSurplus 141 825 34\nLoans 843 583 74\u2018,\\\nDeposits 938 163 53\nDaily Working Cash Exchange and o\nLawful Resrve 274 521 17\nTotal Assets 1 279 988 87\nBORROWED MONEY NONE.\nTake notice from this statement that in times like\nthese, when nearly everybody owes money, both\nlarge and small, this bank OWES NOTHING AT ALL.\nBanks generally in times like these have to borrow\nfrom the great money centers when deposits are\nlow, but our deposits have held up splendidly,\nbecause of our established strength, and we have\nbeen perfectly comfortable and at ease, well able\nto take care of every legitimate demand upon us\nfor carrying on business in our territory.\nFor such an enviable situation we are indebted tB\na large and growing patronage, and our sound\nfinancial condition is also due t\u00a2 the foresight\nof our managers who stay close to shore in timss\nwhen there is not so much calm sailing.\nWith our large resources and expe#ience, we are\nmaking plans for helping to bring back the happy\nreturn of prosperity which we predict is sure to\ncome if we labor wisely and faint.not.\nTHE EXCHANGE NATIONAL BANK.,\nThe bank that has outgrown it's present house and\n1s showing it's faith in the future of this section\nby building a handsome and adequate house for\nits enlarging operations.\nMiss Edith Thomas left last week\nfor a visit with friends in Americus.\nthe funeral of her niece Addie Re Eng_\nfrom Oglethorpe where she attended\nthe funeral of her niece Addi Re Eng\nlish,\nMiss Daisy Mc\u00dfae spent Sunday in\nAbbeville with her parents.\nDress Sale\nBig Shipment of Ladie\u2019s\nNew Fall Dresses, all the\nNew Fall Styles, Materials\nand Colors--\nPut on Special at--\n$3.435, $3.90, $4.20,\n$6.90, $8.90 and up\nat Sale\nBig Shipment of Men\u2019s\nVelour and Beaver Hats\nin the New Fall Shapes\nand Colors--\nVelours $2.48 up\nBeavers $\u00a73.90 up\nThe\nSurprise Store\nMr. and Mrs. Matthias are spending\na few days in Rochelle with their\ndaughter Mrs. Otto Holt.\nMr. and Mrs, H, Garber spent Sun\nday in Tifton.\net P\nMr. Horace Dixon left Sund\u2018,:\u2018qr v\nMiami where he has accepted a posi\ntion","height":"28889","width":"21368"}}
